    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a great start, thanks. My students might ask about the critics, though. Some legal scholars say that 'substantive due process' is actually a bit problematic or even unconstitutional because it lets judges make up rights that aren't written down. How would you address those criticisms in the lesson?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics argue that substantive due process allows judges to engage in judicial activism, essentially creating new rights not explicitly granted in the text of the Constitution. This viewpoint is a major concern because it allows unelected judges to substitute their personal policy preferences for the will of the people expressed through elected representatives. However, proponents argue that the Constitution is meant to protect fundamental human dignity, which requires courts to interpret the spirit of liberty, not just the letter of the law.",
      "source": "target",
